      <p class="mt-5 font-light! md:text-xl text-base-content">In Bonfire, in order to edit an existing extension and test the changes you need to set up the extension in your development environment. The process is quite straightforward:</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-4xl text-center font-bold tracking-tight leading-normal! mb-10 text-base-content">Fork the extension</h2>

      <p class="mt-5 font-light! md:text-xl text-base-content">
       If you want to share your changes to the extension, you may want to first fork it on Github. <br />

        Use <code>just dep-clone *dep* *repo*</code> to clone an extension from its Git repository. Replace <i>dep</i> with the extension name and <i>repo</i> with the full URL of your fork. The cloned extension will be cloned in <code>./extensions</code>:</p>
       
       {% highlight "bash" %}
       just dep-clone-local bonfire_social https://github.com/my_username/bonfire_social
        {% endhighlight %}

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-4xl text-center font-bold tracking-tight leading-normal! mb-10 text-base-content">Enable the extension</h2>
      <p class="mt-5 font-light! md:text-xl text-base-content">
        After cloning, choose to use the local version by editing <code>./config/deps.path</code> (create the file if it doesnâ€™t exist). <br/>
        The format to follow is the following: <code>dep_name = "dep_path" </code>.<br/>
        To disable a local extension, comment or delete its line in .deps.path.<br/>
        Use just dev to run the app with changes hot-reloading.
      </p>
      {% highlight "bash" %}
      # ./config/deps.path
bonfire_me = "./extensions/bonfire_me"
# bonfire_boundaries = "./extensions/bonfire_boundaries" # disabled local copy
      {% endhighlight %}


